  "prompt": "Can the statement \"X is n times less or smaller than Y be justified when n>1?",
  "response": "The phrasing \"X is n times less than Y\" can be confusing and is often considered ambiguous or incorrect in mathematical terms. When using this phrase, the meaning is not universally clear, and it can lead to misinterpretation.\n\nIf you mean that X is a fraction of Y (e.g., X is a certain proportion of Y), it is clearer to state how X relates to Y using multiplication or division. For example, if you mean \"X is \\( \\frac{1}{n} \\) of Y,\" you could say \"X is \\( \\frac{Y}{n} \\)\" or \"X is Y divided by n.\"\n\nOn the other hand, saying \"X is n times smaller than Y\" is also misleading unless it is properly defined because it may imply subtraction rather than division. \n\nIn summary, to avoid ambiguity, it is better to use clearer expressions like \"X is \\( \\frac{1}{n} \\) of Y\" instead of \"X is n times less than Y\" or \"X is n times smaller than Y.\"",
